# React + Vite — Quality (Part 4)

## 17. Performance System

Performance must be measurable and enforced.

Key practices:
- Code-splitting with `React.lazy` and route-based chunking.
- Memoize heavy computations (`useMemo`, `useCallback`, `React.memo`).
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders (proper keys, immutable updates).
- Use web-worker for expensive background work (if needed).
- Tree-shakeable imports and avoid large polyfills.

Vite build manualChunks (see `vite.config.ts` in Part 1).

Bundle budgets (CI): Use `rollup-plugin-visualizer` or `esbuild` size checks and fail CI if budget exceeded (example budgets: initial JS < 200KB gzipped).

Lighthouse in CI: Run Lighthouse or PageSpeed checks and enforce thresholds:
- Performance >= 90
- Largest Contentful Paint < 2.5s
- Interaction to Next Paint (INP) < 200ms

## 18. SEO System

For SPA SEO management use `react-helmet-async` and SSR prerender where needed.

Install:

```bash
npm install react-helmet-async
```

Provider:

```tsx
import { HelmetProvider } from 'react-helmet-async'

<HelmetProvider>
  <App />
</HelmetProvider>
```

Page example:

```tsx
import { Helmet } from 'react-helmet-async'

export function SomePage() {
  return (
    <>
      <Helmet>
        <title>Page Title — Product</title>
        <meta name="description" content="Short page description" />
        <link rel="canonical" href="https://example.com/page" />
        <meta property="og:title" content="OG Title" />
        <meta property="og:description" content="OG Description" />
        <meta name="twitter:card" content="summary_large_image" />
      </Helmet>
      {/* page content */}
    </>
  )
}
```

Additional SEO notes:
- Server-side render (SSR) or Static Generation (SSG) for important landing pages. Use tools like Vercel / Astro / Next if SEO-critical.
- Generate `sitemap.xml` and `robots.txt` in CI.
- Use structured data (JSON-LD) for rich results.
- Ensure pages have descriptive `<title>` and `<meta description>` and canonical links.

## 19. Image Optimization

- Prefer AVIF/WebP for production.
- Use `loading="lazy"`.
- Use `srcset` and responsive sizes.
- Consider an image CDN (Cloudflare Images, Imgix, etc.).
- Compress images during CI or as part of asset pipeline.

Example:

```html
<img loading="lazy" src="/images/hero.avif" alt="..." width="1200" height="600" />
```

## 20. Accessibility (A11y)

- Semantic HTML.
- Keyboard navigation.
- ARIA where necessary.
- Color contrast checks.
- Test with axe and Lighthouse.

Example:

```tsx
<button aria-label="Close dialog">×</button>
```

### 20a. Semantic Tags

Use semantic elements instead of generic `div`/`span` where meaning exists:

| Element | Use |
|---------|-----|
| `<header>` | Site or section header (logo, nav) |
| `<main>` | Primary page content (one per page) |
| `<nav>` | Navigation links |
| `<article>` | Self-contained content (post, card) |
| `<section>` | Thematic grouping with heading |
| `<aside>` | Tangential content (sidebar) |
| `<footer>` | Site or section footer |
| `<figure>` + `<figcaption>` | Images/charts with captions |
| `<h1>`–`<h6>` | Heading hierarchy (no skips) |

Landmark structure example:

```tsx
<>
  <header><nav>...</nav></header>
  <main>
    <article>
      <h1>Title</h1>
      <section>...</section>
    </article>
  </main>
  <aside>...</aside>
  <footer>...</footer>
</>
```

### 20b. Component Accessibility

- **Buttons**: Use `<button>` for actions; avoid `div` with `onClick`. Add `aria-label` if label is only visual (e.g. icon-only).
- **Links**: Use `<a href>` for navigation; `button` for actions that don’t change URL.
- **Forms**: Always pair `<label htmlFor={id}>` with inputs; use `aria-describedby` for helper text and `aria-invalid` for errors.
- **Images**: Provide meaningful `alt`; use `alt=""` for decorative images.
- **Modals/Dialogs**: Use `role="dialog"`, `aria-modal`, `aria-labelledby`, `aria-describedby`; trap focus; restore focus on close.
- **Lists**: Use `<ul>`/`<ol>` with `<li>` for lists, not `div`s.
- **Custom controls**: Mirror native semantics (ARIA `role`, `aria-expanded`, `aria-pressed`, etc.) and keyboard support (Enter, Space, Arrow keys).

Focus management: ensure focus moves logically; trap focus in modals; restore focus on close.

### 20c. Automated A11y Tests

Use `jest-axe` or `@axe-core/react` in component tests. Catch violations early.

```ts
import { axe, toHaveNoViolations } from 'jest-axe'
expect.extend(toHaveNoViolations)

test('Button has no a11y violations', async () => {
  const { container } = render(<Button>Submit</Button>)
  const results = await axe(container)
  expect(results).toHaveNoViolations()
})
```

### 20d. Layout Shift (CLS)

Reserve space for dynamic content. Use `min-height` or skeleton with same dimensions as final content. Avoid inserting content above existing content. Set `width` and `height` on images to prevent reflow.

### 20e. Virtualization

For long lists (100+ items), use `react-window`, `@tanstack/react-virtual`, or `react-virtualized`. Render only visible items. Improves performance and scroll smoothness.

## 21. Testing

- Unit + component tests: Vitest + React Testing Library.
- Integration: use MSW to mock APIs.
- E2E: Playwright (recommended) or Cypress.

Example unit test:

```ts
import { render, screen } from '@testing-library/react'
import userEvent from '@testing-library/user-event'
import Button from './Button'

test('button renders', () => {
  render(<Button>Click</Button>)
  expect(screen.getByText('Click')).toBeInTheDocument()
})
```

## 21b. MSW Setup

Install `msw`. Create handlers in `src/mocks/handlers.ts` and server in `src/mocks/server.ts`. Use `server.listen()` in `setupTests.ts` (or vitest setup file). Structure handlers by endpoint; reuse for unit and E2E where possible.

```ts
// mocks/handlers.ts
import { http, HttpResponse } from 'msw'

export const handlers = [
  http.get('/api/users', () => HttpResponse.json([{ id: '1', name: 'Test' }]))
]
```

## 21c. E2E Structure (Playwright)

```
e2e/
├─ fixtures/
├─ tests/
│  ├─ auth.spec.ts
│  └─ dashboard.spec.ts
├─ playwright.config.ts
└─ global-setup.ts
```

Use Page Object pattern for complex flows. Run `npx playwright test` in CI.

## 21d. Coverage Thresholds

Vitest coverage in `vitest.config.ts`:

```ts
coverage: {
  provider: 'v8',
  reporter: ['text', 'lcov'],
  thresholds: {
    lines: 70,
    functions: 70,
    branches: 65
  }
}
```

## 21e. Test Fixtures

Store mock data in `tests/fixtures/` or `src/mocks/fixtures/`. Export factories (e.g. `createUser(overrides)`) for flexible test data. Keep fixtures aligned with Zod schemas.

## 21f. Component Test Patterns

- Prefer `getByRole`, `getByLabelText` over `getByTestId`.
- Use `userEvent` over `fireEvent` for interactions.
- For async: `waitFor`, `findBy*` queries.
- Wrap with necessary providers (Redux, QueryClient, Router) in custom `render` helper.

## 21g. Regression tests & debugging

- **Framework**: Vitest + React Testing Library.
- **Location**: Co-locate `*.test.tsx` or `**/__tests__/*.test.tsx`; E2E in `e2e/tests/*.spec.ts`.
- **Commands**: `npm test` or `npm run test`; `npm run lint`; `npm run type-check`.
- **Regression**: Add `test('handles [bug scenario] - regression', ...)` that would have caught the bug.
- **Verify**: `npm test` and `npm run lint` pass before commit.

## 22. Linting & Formatting

`.eslintrc.cjs` (example):

```js
module.exports = {
  root: true,
  env: { browser: true, es2021: true },
  extends: [
    'eslint:recommended',
    'plugin:react/recommended',
    'plugin:react-hooks/recommended',
    'prettier'
  ],
  rules: {
    'react/react-in-jsx-scope': 'off',
    'no-console': ['warn', { allow: ['warn', 'error'] }]
  }
}
```

`.prettierrc`:

```json
{
  "semi": false,
  "singleQuote": true,
  "trailingComma": "all",
  "printWidth": 100
}
```

Run `lint` and `format` in pre-commit hooks (see Part 5 — Husky).
